[[Category: of heaven, earth, and all living things. It is also written as '''産霊''', '''産巣日''', '''産日''', or '''産魂'''.

== Overview ==
The term "musubi" (産) is derived from "umusu" (産むす), with "umu" (to produce) removed, suggesting natural emergence. The "hi" (霊) represents spiritual or mystical energy. In Shinto, all things are believed to arise and develop through the working of "musubi." It is one of the fundamental ideas in Shinto, and its significance has been discussed by {{ill|Kokugaku|ja|国学|12=draft}} scholars since the Edo period.

Many deities with the word "musubi" in their names are thought to embody this creative force.

Among the {{ill|Three Deities of Creation|ja|造化三神|12=draft}}, there are the deities {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|タカミムスビ|1=Takamimusubi|1=Takamimusubi|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kamimusubi|ja|カミムスビ|1=Kamimusubi|1=Kamimusubi|12=draft}}. Takamimusubi played a key role in commanding the deities to bring back {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|12=draft}} when she hid in the {{ill|Heavenly Rock Cave|ja|天岩戸|1=Amano-Iwato|lt=Heavenly Rock Cave|12=draft}}, while Kamimusubi revived the slain {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|12=draft}}. These acts demonstrate that the "musubi" deities are associated with invigorating a waning spirit, symbolizing vitality and life force.

Among the {{ill|Eight Imperial Deities|ja|宮中八神|12=draft}} enshrined in the {{ill|Imperial Palace|ja|宮中|12=draft}}, five include "musubi" in their names: Kamimusubi (神産日神), Takamimusubi (高御産日神), Tamatsume-Musubi (玉積産日神), Ikumusubi (生産日神), and Tarumusubi (足産日神). Tamatsume-Musubi, also known as "Tamodome-Musubi" in the *{{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|12=draft}}*, represents the act of anchoring the soul within the body ({{ill|Chinkon|ja|鎮魂|12=draft}}). Ikumusubi, derived from "iki" (生き, breath), signifies life and vitality. Tarumusubi indicates fullness and abundance in its active force.

The alternate name for {{ill|Kagutsuchi|ja|カグツチ|12=draft}} is "Homusubi" (火産霊). According to myth, {{ill|Izanami|ja|イザナミ|12=draft}} dies after giving birth to Kagutsuchi, the fire god, due to severe burns. Enraged, {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ|12=draft}} kills Kagutsuchi, and many gods are born from this act. Kagutsuchi is thus considered a "musubi" deity, embodying the symbolism of life's continuity and renewal, even in death. Similar themes are observed in the story of {{ill|Wakumusubi|ja|ワクムスビ|12=draft}}, who generates grains and plants after death in the *{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}*.

